The Fatal Error: Missing Struct Field
This is the exact error causing your Docker build to fail:

Plaintext
329.0 error[E0063]: missing field `patient_id` in initializer of `BedTransitionRequest`
329.0   --> services/web/src/pages/bedboard.rs:51:43
The Cause:
In Rust, when you create an instance of a struct, you must provide a value for every single field defined in that struct. On line 51 of services/web/src/pages/bedboard.rs, you are creating a BedTransitionRequest, but you forgot to include the patient_id field.

The Fix:
Open services/web/src/pages/bedboard.rs and look around line 51. You need to add the missing patient_id. It probably looks something like this right now:

Rust
// Current broken code
let req = BedTransitionRequest {
    transition_action: some_action,
    transition_state: some_state,
    // ... missing patient_id
};
You need to update it to include the missing field:

Rust
// Fixed code
let req = BedTransitionRequest {
    patient_id: 123, // <-- ADD THIS (use the actual variable holding the patient ID)
    transition_action: some_action,
    transition_state: some_state,
};
The Warnings: Unnecessary mut with Signals
The rest of the output is a massive wall of warnings from services/web/src/main.rs. While these won't stop your build from completing (only the error above will do that), fixing them will clean up your logs.

Plaintext
329.7 warning: variable does not need to be mutable
329.7   --> services/web/src/main.rs:115:9
329.7     |
329.7 115 |     let mut patient_query = use_signal(String::new);
The Cause:
You are using the Dioxus framework. In Dioxus, use_signal returns a type that uses interior mutability. This means you do not need to declare the variable holding the signal as mutable (mut) in order to change the data inside it.

The Fix:
Go through services/web/src/main.rs (lines 115 through 144) and remove the mut keyword from all your signal declarations.

Change this:

Rust
let mut patient_query = use_signal(String::new);
let mut patient_results = use_signal(Vec::<PatientSearchResultDto>::new);
To this:

Rust
let patient_query = use_signal(String::new);
let patient_results = use_signal(Vec::<PatientSearchResultDto>::new);
Once you add the missing patient_id in bedboard.rs, your docker compose build should succeed!

